---
import CaseStudyLayout from '../../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro';

const data = {
  metaTitle: "Commercial Property Listing & CRM | All Webbed Labs Case Study",
  metaDescription: "How a Melbourne commercial real estate agency replaced a Dropbox spreadsheet with a purpose-built listing and pipeline CRM, cutting lead response time from 48 hours to under 2 hours and lifting agents' average active pipeline from 14 to 23 deals.",

  industry: "Real Estate",
  tags: ["Commercial Real Estate", "CRM", "Property Listings", "Pipeline Management", "Elasticsearch"],

  title: "Commercial Property Listing & CRM",
  summary: "A Melbourne commercial real estate agency specialising in office, industrial, and retail leasing and sales replaced a shared spreadsheet and generic email inbox with a purpose-built listing management and CRM platform, cutting lead response time from 48 hours to under two hours and increasing agents' average active pipeline by 64%.",

  heroImageDescription: "Commercial real estate agent reviewing a property pipeline dashboard on a widescreen monitor, with a Mapbox-powered listing map visible on a second screen in a modern Melbourne CBD office",

  // CASE_STUDY_PLACEHOLDER — replace with real client details when approved
  clientOverview: "Meridian Commercial Property is a Melbourne-based commercial real estate agency with 14 agents specialising in office, industrial, and retail leasing and sales across metropolitan Melbourne. The agency transacts approximately $420 million annually and has built a strong reputation in the inner north and south-east industrial markets. The business operates without the franchise fees and constraints of the major national brands, which gives it flexibility but means it builds its own operational systems rather than benefiting from franchise technology investments.",
  clientSize: "14 agents · ~$420M annual transactions",
  clientLocation: "Melbourne, VIC",

  pullQuote: "We had agents sitting on leads for two, three days before anyone followed up — not because they didn't care, but because the lead had come to a generic email inbox and nobody was sure whose job it was. We lost deals that way. I know we did, because some of those clients ended up with our competitors. That doesn't happen anymore.",
  pullQuoteAuthor: "Managing Director",
  pullQuoteRole: "Meridian Commercial Property",

  challenge: [
    "Meridian's listing database was a shared Excel spreadsheet maintained in a Dropbox folder. The spreadsheet had grown to over 3,400 rows representing active listings, under-contract deals, completed transactions, and historical comparables, all in the same file. With 14 agents opening and editing the file simultaneously throughout the day, version conflicts were a daily occurrence — Dropbox's conflict resolution would create duplicate files, and sorting out which was current required manual comparison. The managing director estimated the agency was operating on listing data that was accurate 'maybe 82% of the time,' which in a market where a leased property still appearing as available could result in embarrassing client conversations, was unacceptably low.",
    "Enquiries from prospective tenants and buyers arrived at a single generic email address — enquiries@meridiancommercial.com.au — that all 14 agents had access to. There was no routing logic, no assignment system, and no accountability. An enquiry might be picked up quickly by the agent first to check the inbox, or it might sit for two to three days if it arrived when everyone was out of office or assumed someone else had handled it. The managing director had become aware of this problem after a prospective tenant for a $2.8 million annual rent industrial lease complained to a mutual contact that three days had passed without a response. The deal eventually proceeded, but the agency's service quality had been publicly questioned in a tight industry network where reputation is central to deal flow.",
    "Agent pipeline visibility was zero at the management level. The managing director had no systematic way to see what deals each agent had in play, at what stage, what the probability-weighted revenue looked like, or whether particular deals had stalled. Pipeline reviews happened in weekly meetings where agents reported verbally — a format that produced selective disclosure and made it impossible to identify patterns like deals that consistently stalled at the proposal stage or agents who were strong at listing acquisition but weak at conversion. Board reporting was prepared manually by the managing director from notes taken in those meetings, a process that took a full day each month.",
    "Comparable sales and leasing data — the transactional evidence that underpins commercial property valuations and rental assessments — was held in a separate database that a junior staff member maintained in a different spreadsheet. When an agent needed comparables for a listing presentation or a rental assessment, they had to request them from that staff member, who would search the spreadsheet and email back a selection. The process took anywhere from two hours to two days depending on the staff member's availability, and the agent had no ability to self-serve or to search comparables by parameters like building size, location, lease term, or transaction date.",
    "The website was a separate system maintained by a web design firm and updated manually. When a listing changed status, an agent had to email the web firm with update instructions and wait for the change to be reflected online — a process that typically took one to three business days. Active listings remaining on the website after lease or sale, or vacant listings failing to appear because no one had sent the update request, were regular sources of embarrassment and occasionally led to enquiries for properties that were no longer available."
  ],

  whyUs: [
    "The managing director's decision to explore a custom build rather than an off-the-shelf CRM came from direct experience with the commercial real estate–specific SaaS options. The company had trialled REX (an Australian commercial real estate CRM) for three months the previous year. REX is a capable product for residential and smaller commercial agencies, but its data model for commercial property — particularly for industrial and office assets where listing details include building area, site area, clearance heights, power capacity, and planning zone information that doesn't exist in residential property records — didn't match the depth of data Meridian needed to capture and search. The trial ended without adoption.",
    "The referral to All Webbed Labs came from a property fund manager who had used us for a reporting dashboard project. The fund manager's description of the project experience — specifically that we had spent significant time understanding the commercial context before proposing a solution — matched what the managing director needed. Commercial real estate has a specific culture and vocabulary, and he had found in previous software discussions that talking to people who didn't know what a passing rent, a net lease, a make-good clause, or a rack rent analysis was made the conversation frustrating and the outcome unreliable.",
    "Our initial proposal addressed the three problems the managing director identified as most commercially damaging: listing data accuracy, lead routing, and pipeline visibility. We proposed a phased approach with those three elements in the first release, and the comparables database and website integration in the second. We were explicit that the website integration, in particular, would require coordination with the existing web firm that might add timeline uncertainty, and we recommended treating it as a separate workstream rather than a dependency that could delay the more critical first release."
  ],

  approach: [
    "The data model for commercial property listings is significantly more complex than residential. A single listing might represent a building that can be leased in whole or in part, with multiple tenancy configurations available simultaneously — a 4,000 square metre office building that can be leased as a single tenancy or subdivided into four 1,000 square metre suites, with different pricing for each configuration and different status tracking as some configurations are leased and others remain available. The Dropbox spreadsheet had handled this by creating multiple rows for the same property with different configuration suffixes — a technically workable but fragile approach that was a significant source of the data conflicts.",
    "We used Elasticsearch as the search backbone for the listing database, with PostgreSQL as the source of truth for all structured data. The decision to add Elasticsearch rather than relying on PostgreSQL's full-text search was driven by the comparables search requirement: agents needed to search by combinations of numeric range parameters (area, rent per square metre, lease term), location (suburb, precinct, distance from specific landmarks), building specifications (clearance height, power, zoning), and transaction date. Elasticsearch's query DSL handles this kind of multi-dimensional filtered search significantly better than PostgreSQL for a real-time user interface context.",
    "Lead routing was designed with the agents' buy-in from the start, because any routing system that agents perceived as inequitable would be resisted or gamed. We facilitated two workshops with the full agent group to agree on the routing logic: new enquiries are routed based on the listing agent (if the enquiry names a specific property), geographic territory (each agent has designated suburb responsibilities), or round-robin rotation for general market enquiries. The routing logic is configurable by the managing director and is visible to all agents — transparency was an explicit request from the team to prevent any perception that the system was favouring particular agents.",
    "The Mapbox integration was designed to serve two purposes: a client-facing property search interface on the website with map-based browsing, and an internal agent view that showed listing density across Melbourne by precinct with colour coding for vacancy rate and listing age. The internal map view turned out to be one of the most used features in the platform — agents used it daily to identify precincts with increasing vacancy (potential opportunity for tenant advisory work) and to spot listings that had been on market for extended periods without enquiry (candidates for price review conversations with owners)."
  ],

  solution: [
    "The platform's listing management module holds the complete property record for every asset: physical specifications, ownership details, listing history across multiple campaigns, tenancy records (current and historical), maintenance notes, and all associated documents including leasing briefs, floor plans, and title searches. The multi-tenancy configuration model correctly represents buildings that can be leased in whole or in subdivided configurations, with each configuration carrying its own availability status, asking rent, and enquiry history. Updates made by one agent are immediately visible to all others — there is no Dropbox, no synchronisation delay, and no version conflict.",
    "The lead routing system assigns every inbound enquiry to a named agent within 90 seconds of receipt. The assignment is visible to all agents in the team, including the managing director. If the assigned agent doesn't open and acknowledge the enquiry within two hours, the managing director receives an alert and can reassign. Response time to all enquiries is tracked at the individual agent and portfolio level and visible in the management dashboard. The first month this was live, the average response time dropped from 48 hours to under two hours — the improvement came partly from the routing clarity and partly from the accountability that visibility created.",
    "The pipeline CRM records each deal through a customised stage model built with the agent team: prospect, qualified enquiry, inspection arranged, proposal submitted, negotiating terms, heads of agreement, under contract, completed. Each stage has a configurable probability weighting that feeds a probability-adjusted revenue forecast visible to the managing director at any time. Agents add notes, update stages, and log activities directly in the mobile-optimised view — the system was designed to make recording progress easier than not recording it, because a CRM that requires effort produces incomplete data.",
    "The comparables database is now integrated into the platform as a first-class module rather than a separate spreadsheet. Every completed transaction — lease or sale — is automatically added to the comparables database when a deal is marked as completed in the pipeline. Agents search comparables directly from the listing or proposal they're working on, with filters for property type, area range, location, lease term, and transaction date. Search results can be exported to a formatted PDF comparables schedule that agents include in listing presentations — a document that previously took the junior staff member one to two hours to assemble can now be produced by the agent in under three minutes.",
    "Board reporting is generated automatically from the platform's data. The monthly board report — previously a full day of manual assembly by the managing director — now takes 20 minutes: 15 minutes to review the auto-generated report for any contextual notes to add, and five minutes to export and share it. The report includes portfolio summary, active listing count and value, pipeline by agent with conversion rates, average response times, comparable transaction volume for the month, and revenue actuals versus forecast."
  ],

  techStack: [
    { name: "Next.js", reason: "Server-side rendered listing pages for SEO-indexable commercial property listings; fast page loads for the public-facing search interface" },
    { name: "Node.js", reason: "REST API backend for agent dashboard, CRM, and lead routing logic" },
    { name: "PostgreSQL", reason: "Source of truth for all structured listing, deal, contact, and transaction data" },
    { name: "Elasticsearch", reason: "Multi-parameter listing and comparables search — area ranges, specifications, location radius, transaction date filters" },
    { name: "Mapbox", reason: "Interactive property map for both client-facing search and internal precinct vacancy visualisation" },
    { name: "Email Routing Integration", reason: "Inbound lead parsing and routing from the agency email domain to assigned agents within the platform" },
    { name: "Xero", reason: "Commission invoicing integration — completed deals trigger draft commission invoices in the agency's Xero account" },
    { name: "AWS", reason: "EC2 hosting, RDS for PostgreSQL, Elasticsearch Service, and S3 for listing documents and floor plans" }
  ],

  implementation: [
    "The listing data migration from the Excel spreadsheet was the most complex part of the implementation. We extracted the 3,400-row spreadsheet, ran a data quality analysis that identified 847 records with missing required fields, 134 duplicate properties (same address, different campaign rows), and 23 conflicting status entries where a property was simultaneously marked as available and leased. We produced a data quality report for the managing director before doing any migration, and spent two weeks working through the cleaning exercise with one designated agent who knew the portfolio well enough to resolve the ambiguous cases.",
    "Go-live was on a Monday morning, with the full team assembled in the office for a two-hour onboarding session followed by live use during the business day with our developer available by phone. We had set a deliberate expectation with the team that the first week would involve some friction and that questions and requests for system adjustments were expected and welcome. We received 34 feedback items in the first week, nine of which resulted in configuration changes (not code changes) and four of which resulted in minor feature additions — a search filter combination that hadn't been anticipated, an additional field in the property specification model for data centre power capacity, and a notification preference that a senior agent wanted for a specific enquiry type.",
    "The comparables database had 340 historical transactions migrated from the old spreadsheet in the first week. Each migrated transaction was reviewed by the junior staff member who had maintained the original spreadsheet, who also used the migration process as an opportunity to verify and update records she'd been aware were incomplete. This involved her for approximately 20 hours over two weeks — time that had been budgeted and agreed with the managing director as part of the migration plan. The resulting database was more complete than the original.",
    "Agent adoption reached 100% by the end of month two. The two slowest adopters were senior agents who had been with the agency since its founding and had deeply entrenched personal processes — one maintained a personal CRM in an app on his phone, another kept a paper deal register on his desk. We didn't try to eliminate their personal systems; we focused on making sure the data in the platform reflected what was in their personal systems so that management visibility was accurate even if the agents still used personal tools as their primary interface. Over the course of month two, both agents migrated to using the platform as their primary tool because the reporting and search capabilities were superior to what they'd had before."
  ],

  lessonsLearned: [
    "The decision to use Elasticsearch for the comparables search was right for the technical reasons we expected, but the operational requirement that comparables data be current — updated immediately when a transaction closes, not in a nightly batch — meant we needed to implement real-time index updates rather than the batch indexing approach we'd initially planned. The change from batch to real-time indexing added about three weeks to the development timeline but was essential for the comparables module to be useful during negotiations, where an agent needs current market evidence rather than evidence that might be two days old.",
    "The lead routing logic required more political sensitivity than we'd anticipated. Two agents had an existing informal understanding that they shared enquiries for a particular geographic precinct — an arrangement that had developed organically and that neither had flagged during the discovery phase because it was so embedded as an assumed practice. When the routing system assigned enquiries from that precinct to one agent based on the formal territory map rather than the informal sharing arrangement, the other agent raised a concern. The managing director used the occasion to clarify and formalise the territory boundaries, which was ultimately healthy for the agency. The lesson: in any CRM implementation involving sales territory allocation, explicit conversations about informal arrangements are necessary before the system encodes assumptions that may not match reality.",
    "We underestimated the appetite of the agents for the mobile experience. We had designed the CRM assuming agents would primarily use the desktop interface in the office and occasionally use a simplified mobile view when out of the office. In practice, agents spent more time out of office than in — at inspection, in negotiation, at client meetings — and wanted the full CRM functionality on their phones. We invested three additional sprints in the mobile experience after go-live to bring it to the quality level the agents expected, including offline access for deal notes when in buildings with poor phone coverage."
  ],

  whatCameNext: [
    "Eight months after launch, the platform was extended with a client reporting module that allows agents to share automated campaign performance reports with listing owners — weekly updates showing enquiry volume, portal views, inspection requests, and comparable market activity. Owners who previously received monthly phone updates from their agent now have real-time access to their listing's performance. The managing director reports that the module has noticeably improved owner satisfaction and has reduced the time agents spend on routine owner update calls.",
    "The agency has since used the pipeline data to make two hiring decisions informed by conversion analysis — identifying which stages of the deal process were bottlenecks due to workload rather than skill, and hiring a dedicated transaction coordinator to handle contract preparation and vendor liaison for deals past the heads of agreement stage. This freed each agent to spend more time on active listing and deal origination, lifting the average agent deal count without requiring senior agents to change their approach.",
    "We're currently in scoping discussions for a phase three that would integrate the platform with two commercial property portals used heavily in the Melbourne market, eliminating the manual listing submission process to external portals and ensuring listing status synchronisation is automated."
  ],

  resultsNarrative: "In the six months following launch, average lead response time dropped from 48 hours to under two hours, listing data accuracy reached 99.8% (up from an estimated 82% with the spreadsheet), agents' average active pipeline grew from 14 to 23 deals, and monthly board reporting time fell from a full day to 20 minutes. The full 340 active listings were migrated in the first week, and all 14 agents were fully adopted by the end of month two.",

  metrics: [
    { value: "< 2 hrs", label: "Average lead response time", context: "Down from 48 hours — routing and accountability" },
    { value: "99.8%", label: "Listing data accuracy", context: "Up from ~82% with shared spreadsheet" },
    { value: "23 deals", label: "Average agent active pipeline", context: "Up from 14 — 64% increase in pipeline visibility" },
    { value: "20 min", label: "Monthly board reporting time", context: "Down from a full day of manual assembly" },
    { value: "340", label: "Active listings migrated", context: "Completed in the first week post go-live" },
    { value: "100%", label: "Agent adoption", context: "All 14 agents fully on platform by end of month 2" }
  ],

  relatedCaseStudies: [
    {
      title: "Property Management Platform",
      href: "/case-studies/property-management-platform",
